SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 703
By Hatcher
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Jennifer Wackerhagen
for her contributions to United Way of Blount
County and to the State of Tennessee.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should salute those
citizens who, through their extraordinary efforts, have distinguished themselves as community
leaders of whom we can all be proud; and
WHEREAS, one such noteworthy person is Jennifer Wackerhagen, a highly respected
member of her community who has dedicated herself to improving the quality of life for her
fellow citizens through twenty-five years of service with United Way of Blount County; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Wackerhagen is a 1993 graduate of Alcoa High School, and she
earned her bachelor's degree in communications from the University of Tennessee in 1997; and
WHEREAS, Jennifer Wackerhagen began working at United Way of Blount County in
January 2001, during which time she served as Communications and Marketing Director; in
2006, she was promoted to Vice President of Resource Development and became President
and Chief Executive Officer in 2013; and
WHEREAS, during her time as Communications and Marketing Director, Ms.
Wackerhagen did not even have an office, just a desk tucked in the hallway; however, her
passion, grit, genuine care for others, and commitment to serving her community helped her
become an indispensable member of the United Way team; and
WHEREAS, Jennifer Wackerhagen quickly rose to the role of Vice President of
Resource Development and led annual campaigns, coordinated large-scale fundraising events,
and mobilized hundreds of dedicated volunteers to raise funds; over the last twenty-five years,
United Way of Blount County has raised more than $50 million, which has translated to stronger
nonprofits, expanded services, and hope for over 750,000 neighbors in need; and
SJR0703
013045
- 1 -

WHEREAS, in 2013, Ms. Wackerhagen was named President and CEO of United Way
of Blount County, in which position her caring nature, volunteer spirit, and steadfast work ethic
have continued to shine; she has built an organization with incredible community impact and
defined what it means to serve with purpose, empathy, and collaboration; and
WHEREAS, for more than two decades, Jennifer Wackerhagen has poured her passion
for community service into shaping the mission of United Way of Blount County, strengthening
partnerships and fueling real impact for people within the county; and
WHEREAS, since 2012, United Way of Blount County has received consecutive four-
star ratings from Charity Navigator, a rank held by only seven percent of charities evaluated by
Charity Navigator; this highlights the high performance and transparency of the organization;
and
WHEREAS, through her tireless leadership, Jennifer Wackerhagen led United Way of
Blount County to be honored by Blount Partnership with the Community Impact Award in 2019;
during the pandemic, her proactive leadership and prioritization of health and safety resulted in
an increase in monetary and in-kind donations to meet the needs of the community; and
WHEREAS, in 2021, Blount County Mayor Ed Mitchell proclaimed January 29th as
Jennifer Wackerhagen Day, in recognition of her then twenty years of service to United Way of
Blount County; and
WHEREAS, in addition to serving her community through her work with United Way, Ms.
Wackerhagen is an active member of her church, Foothills Church, and she was a member of
the 2004 class of Leadership Blount and the East Tennessee Regional Leadership Class of
2008; she received the 20th Anniversary Leadership Blount Alumni Service Award; and
WHEREAS, Jennifer Wackerhagen has served on many boards, including the
Leadership Blount Board; Blount Chamber of Commerce Board of Directors; Junior Service
League, serving as a past board member and parliamentarian; Blount Memorial Hospital's
- 2 - 013045

Internal Review Board; and Blount County Homelessness Task Force as a stakeholder. She
played an integral role in the creation of the Young Leaders Society in 2012 and has helped
mentor other nonprofit directors; and
WHEREAS, it is appropriate that the members of this General Assembly acknowledge
and applaud Ms. Wackerhagen for her dedication to the State of Tennessee and its citizens;
now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Jennifer Wackerhagen for
her twenty-five years of service to United Way of Blount County, her community, and the State
of Tennessee and extend to her our best wishes for much continued success.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
